<subsection xml:id="subsec-reflecting-objects" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Reflecting Objects</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.2 Reflection and Congruence
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Draw an image given an object and a mirror line on plane surface and Cartesian plane
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define reflection as a transformation that moves an object across a mirror line to the opposite side. State the three key properties: (1) image on opposite side, (2) equidistant from mirror line, (3) mirror line is perpendicular bisector of segment joining point to image.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Construct the reflected image of a triangle given a mirror line on a plane surface by drawing perpendiculars and measuring equal distances. Reflect polygons across vertical, horizontal, and diagonal mirror lines. Reflect shapes on the Cartesian plane across x-axis, y-axis, and <m>y = x</m>. Find coordinates of reflected vertices.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply reflection to solve problems involving coordinates. Recognise reflection in real-world contexts (mirrors, water, symmetrical designs). Use reflection to verify congruence.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/reflection-and-congruence/reflecting-objects.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/reflection-and-congruence/step-by-step-guide_reflecting-objects.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Reflecting a Triangle on a Plane (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Groups
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>Is the shape and size of the reflected image the same as the original?</li>
                <li>What do you notice about the distances of corresponding points to the mirror line?</li>
                <li>What is the angle of the segment <m>AA'</m> with the mirror line?</li>
                <li>Where does <m>M</m> intersect <m>AA'</m>?</li>
                <li>What happens if you use a different position for the mirror line?</li>
                <li>Where do you see reflection in real life?</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><q>How do you know the line you drew is perpendicular?</q></li>
                <li><q>What tool would you use to confirm a 90° angle?</q></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Interactive Exploration</alert> If you have an Internet connection, use <xref ref="exploration-mirror"/> to demonstrate how to reflect an object.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert> Provide a small mirror placed along the mirror line so learners can see the reflected image.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Early Finishers:</alert> <q>What happens if a vertex is ON the mirror line?</q>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Observations:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular halign="left">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell>Observation</cell>
                <cell>Expected Answer</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Shape and size</cell>
                <cell>Same (congruence)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Distances to mirror line</cell>
                <cell>Equidistant</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Angle of <m>AA'</m> with mirror line</cell>
                <cell><m>90°</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Where <m>M</m> intersects <m>AA'</m></cell>
                <cell>Mirror line bisects <m>AA'</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_nkg0ez0x">
      <p xml:id="auto_pvjk0j4b">
        <term>Work in groups</term>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_vz9holr3">
        Here is a step by step approach on reflection of a triangle on a plane <m>M.</m>
      </p>
       
      <image>
        <latex-image label="object_mirror_line">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Draw the original triangle
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (-2,3.1) {A};
            \node[blue] at (-4.1,0) {B};
            \node[blue] at (-0.9,-2.1) {C};

            % Draw the mirror line x = 0
            \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,4) node[above right] {$M$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p xml:id="auto_szvhtdk8">
        Draw a perpendicular line from vertex <m>A</m> to the mirror line <m>M</m> and measure the distance by counting the 
        number of squares between vertex <m>A</m> and the mirror line <m>M.</m> Repeat this process for vertices <m>B \text { and }C.</m>
      </p>

      <image>
        <latex-image label="object_mirror_line_perpendicular_distance_1">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Draw the original triangle
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (-2,3.1) {A};
            \node[blue] at (-4.1,0) {B};
            \node[blue] at (-0.9,-2.1) {C};

            % Draw the mirror line x = 0
            \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,4) node[above right] {$M$};

            %Draw the perpendicular distance to M
            \draw[black] (-2,3) -- (0,3);
            \draw[black] (-4,-0) -- (0,0);
            \draw[black] (-1,-2) -- (0,-2);

            %Draw the the angle at the perpendicular bisector
            \draw(-.4,3) -- (-.4,3.4) -- (0,3.4);
            \draw(-.4,0) -- (-.4,.4) -- (0,.4);
            \draw(-.4,-2) -- (-.4,-1.6) -- (0,-1.6);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      
      <p xml:id="auto_ggdk245f">
        Determine the position of the reflected vertices. For vertex <m>A</m> the perpendicular distance between the vertex and the mirror line is 
        <m>2</m> squares. Count <m>2</m> squares from the mirror line to the opposite side of the mirror line and mark that point as <m>A',</m> 
        which is the reflected image of vertex <m>A.</m> Repeat the same procedure the remaining vertices <m>B \text { and }C.</m>
      </p>

      <image>
        <latex-image label="object_mirror_line_perpendicular_distance_2">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Draw the original triangle
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (-2,3.1) {A};
            \node[blue] at (-4.1,0) {B};
            \node[blue] at (-0.9,-2.1) {C};

            % Draw the mirror line x = 0
            \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,4) node[above right] {$M$};

            %Draw the perpendicular distance to M
            \draw[black] (-2,3) -- (2,3) node[green,above right] {$A'$};
            \draw[black] (-4,-0) -- (4,0) node[green,above right] {$B'$};
            \draw[black] (-1,-2) -- (1,-2) node[green,above right] {$C'$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p xml:id="auto_wls7292p">
        Connect the reflected vertices <m>A',B' \text { and }C'</m> to create the reflected image of the triangle <m>ABC.</m>
      </p>

      <image>
        <shortdescription>Reflected triangle</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="triangle-1">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);


            % Draw the original triangle
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-2,3) -- (-4,0) -- (-1,-2) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (-2,3.1) {A};
            \node[blue] at (-4.1,0) {B};
            \node[blue] at (-0.9,-2.1) {C};

            % Draw the mirror line x = 0
            \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,4) node[above right] {$M$};

            %Draw the perpendicular distance from M to the opposite side of the mirror
            \draw[red,black] (-2,3) -- (2,3);
            \draw[red,black] (-4,-0) -- (4,0);
            \draw[red,black] (-1,-2) -- (1,-2);

            % Calculate and draw the reflected triangle
            \fill[green,opacity=0.3] (2,3) -- (4,0) -- (1,-2) -- cycle;
            \draw[green,thick] (2,3) -- (4,0) -- (1,-2)-- cycle;
            \node[green] at (2.2,3.3) {A'};
            \node[green] at (4.3,0.2) {B'};
            \node[green] at (1.5,-1.9) {C'};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

    </activity>
    <exploration xml:id="exploration-mirror">
        <title>Trying Out Reflection</title>
    <p>
        You can try out the activity above with the interactive figure below.  Drag the vertices of the triangle to see how the reflected image changes.  The green triangle is the reflection of the blue triangle across the mirror line <m>x=0.</m> What happens if you drag a point across the mirror line?
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-reflect-polygon-multi">
        <caption>
            The blue triangle is reflected across <m>x = 0</m> to give the green triangle.
        </caption>

        <interactive xml:id="interactive-reflect-poly" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/reflect-polygon-multi.js">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-reflect-polygon-multi" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
        </interactive>
    </figure>
    </exploration>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Guided Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> <q>Reflection does NOT mean just flipping — the image must be flipped across a SPECIFIC mirror line.</q>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
         <p>
            <alert>Three Key Properties of Reflection:</alert>
            <ol>
                <li>The image is on the opposite side of the mirror line from the object.</li>
                <li>Each point and its image are the same distance from the mirror line.</li>
                <li>The mirror line is the perpendicular bisector of the segment joining each point to its image.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Reflection Rules on the Cartesian Plane:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular halign="center">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell>Mirror Line</cell>
                <cell>Rule</cell>
                <cell>Example: <m>A(3,5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>x</m>-axis (<m>y = 0</m>)</cell>
                <cell><m>(x,y) \to (x,-y)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>A'(3,-5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y</m>-axis (<m>x = 0</m>)</cell>
                <cell><m>(x,y) \to (-x,y)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>A'(-3,5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>(x,y) \to (y,x)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>A'(5,3)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>y = -x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>(x,y) \to (-y,-x)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>A'(-5,-3)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Vertical line <m>x = a</m></cell>
                <cell><m>(x,y) \to (2a - x,\, y)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>x = 1: A'(-1,5)</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </insight>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply the learned concepts and procedures to solve varied problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Leaning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners work on a set of problems individually or in pairs. The problems are designed to move from simple classification to application and reasoning.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher monitors Learners as they work, providing support where needed and encouraging Learners to explain their reasoning using the formal properties discussed in the key takeaway.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_hlfinc15">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_ggo7a48m">
          Draw the image of the pentagon under the reflaction on the diagonal mirror line <m>M.</m>
        </p>

        <image>
        <latex-image label="object_mirror_line_example">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Draw the original pentagon
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-1,0) -- (-3,0) -- (-4,2) -- (-2,3.5) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-1,0) -- (-3,0) -- (-4,2) -- (-2,3.5) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
            \node[right,blue] at (-1.2,0) {A};
            \node[blue] at (-3.2,0) {B};
            \node[blue] at (-4.2,2) {C};
            \node[above,blue] at (-1.8,3.5) {D};
            \node[blue] at (0.2,2) {E};

            % Draw the mirror line x = y
            \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (-4,-4) -- (4,4) node[above right] {$M$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p xml:id="auto_5bv3em5a">
          To obtain the image <m>A'</m> of <m>A</m> draw a perpendicular line from <m>A</m> to the mirro line <m>M,</m> extend the 
          line the same distance on the opposite side of the mirror line and mark the point as <m>A'.</m> Similarly, obtain the images 
          <m>B', C', D', E'</m> the images of vertices <m>B, C, D, E</m> respectively.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_9i7lb4vs">
          Connect the images of the vertices to form the reflection of the pentagon. 
        </p> 

        <image>
        <latex-image label="object_mirror_line_example_solution">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Draw the original pentagon
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-1,0) -- (-3,0) -- (-4,2) -- (-2,3.5) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (-1,0) -- (-3,0) -- (-4,2) -- (-2,3.5) -- (0,2) -- cycle;
            \node[right,blue] at (-1.2,0) {A};
            \node[blue] at (-3.2,0) {B};
            \node[blue] at (-4.2,2) {C};
            \node[above,blue] at (-1.8,3.5) {D};
            \node[blue] at (0.2,2) {E};

            % Draw the mirror line x = y
            \draw[red,thick,-&gt;] (-4,-4) -- (4,4) node[above right] {$M$};

            %Draw the perpendicular distance from vertices to the opposite side of the mirror
            \draw[black] (-1,0) -- (0,-1);
            \draw[black] (-3,0) -- (0,-3);
            \draw[black] (-4,2) -- (2,-4);
            \draw[black] (-2,3.5) -- (3.5,-2);
            \draw[black] (0,2) -- (2,0);

            % Draw the image of the pentagon
            \fill[purple,opacity=0.3] (0,-1) -- (0,-3) -- (2,-4) -- (3.5,-2) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[purple,thick] (0,-1) -- (0,-3) -- (2,-4) -- (3.5,-2) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
            \node[left,purple] at (0,-1.2) {A'};
            \node[purple] at (0,-3.2) {B'};
            \node[purple] at (2,-4.2) {C'};
            \node[right,purple] at (3.5,-2.2) {D'};
            \node[purple] at (2.2,0) {E'};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      </solution>
    </example>


