    </exercises>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation and Extension</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Struggling Learners</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Provide grid paper with the mirror line already drawn.</li>
                        <li>Use a small mirror placed on the mirror line to visualise the reflection.</li>
                        <li>Start with vertical and horizontal mirror lines before diagonal ones.</li>
                        <li>Give a step-by-step checklist: (1) draw perpendicular, (2) measure distance, (3) mark image, (4) connect.</li>
                        <li>Use tracing paper to verify reflections by folding along the mirror line.</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>On-Level Learners</title>
                <p>
                    Complete all problems including successive reflections, coordinate rules, and reverse (finding originals from images) problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Advanced Learners</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><q>What single transformation is equivalent to reflecting in <m>y = x</m> then <m>y = 0</m>?</q> (Answer: <m>90°</m> clockwise rotation about the origin.)</li>
                        <li>Investigate reflections in lines of the form <m>y = mx + c</m>.</li>
                        <li>Prove that reflection preserves distances (i.e. the image is congruent to the object).</li>
                        <li>Explore patterns created by multiple mirror lines.</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Extension Challenge 1: Successive Reflections</title>
                <p>
                    <m>\triangle DEF</m> has vertices <m>D(1,1),\, E(4,1),\, F(2,4)</m>.
                    (a) Reflect in the <m>y</m>-axis: <m>D'(-1,1),\, E'(-4,1),\, F'(-2,4)</m>.
                    (b) Reflect the image in the <m>x</m>-axis: <m>D''(-1,-1),\, E''(-4,-1),\, F''(-2,-4)</m>.
                    (c) What single transformation maps <m>\triangle DEF</m> to <m>\triangle D''E''F''</m>? (Answer: rotation of <m>180°</m> about the origin.)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Extension Challenge 2: Symmetry Design</title>
                <p>
                    Draw a shape in Quadrant I, reflect it in the <m>y</m>-axis, then reflect both shapes in the <m>x</m>-axis. You get <m>4</m> copies of the shape, one in each quadrant — a symmetrical design.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Extension Challenge 3: Parallel Mirrors</title>
                <p>
                    If you reflect an object in two parallel mirror lines, the overall result is a translation. The translation distance equals twice the gap between the mirrors.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Extension Challenge 4: Pool Problem</title>
                <p>
                    A swimmer is at <m>(3,2)</m>. Reflection in the <m>x</m>-axis gives <m>(3,-2)</m>. If a mirror is at <m>x = 20</m>, the image is <m>(37,2)</m> (using <m>x' = 2(20) - 3 = 37</m>).
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

